snippet.textDisplay: Shaham it's incorrect to say Abidaji is a legend because of "combination of things that are available in Pakistan". Sufism came with the Sahaba who enriched India with Islam, long time before Pakistan was created. To me APJI has no borders. She belongs to all music lovers in the world. I think it's irrelevant to speculate what kind of singer or whatever she would have been if she was born in my Country.  That was only my sentiment. I might take the liberty of saying that she is worshipped by true music lovers. Lastly sorry Brah, sometime I worry about her after what happened to another great - Amjad Sabri. I wish he was born in my Country too. At least he would be alive today no matter what he became.

snippet.textDisplay: classic sufiana ... Dost’ is structured as an Arifana ghazal but in essence is a kalaam written by Hazrat Baba Zaheen Shah Taji (RA). The kalaam dismisses the previously romanticized pain and suffering of the transient world. The lyrics explores the borderline pain and ecstasy of being fully consumed for the Divine Beloved, as all the friendships and enmities of the fleeting realm hold no purpose and are of no consequence ... relating to Tagore songs where "prem" and "puja" two "prorjas" intersect ... divine music is born ... religion comes second ...
